title: Alice Donut - Dry-Humping The Cash Cow (Live At CBGB) (1994)@fla
description:
Alice Donut, live (ish), and at the height of their powers.  This album was recorded live at CBGB's, and at a private party they played for some bloke.  You may be surprised to hear the massive crowd noise generated, as CBGB's is quite famously a small venue, but so legend has it, the crowd noise was lifted straight from the Kiss Alive album, which the album parodies throughout.  So I'm told anyway, I'm a Donut fan, I've got enough taste not to own anything by the painted clowns of Kiss.

This album contains the finest collection of tunes I own from the late '80s/early 90's.  Tommy Antona's sick, satirically sharp lyrics are squealed out perfectly, his voice soaring, reverberating on those high notes.  The guitars are both punky and psychedelic, giving the band a truly original sound.  The backing vocals create smooth pop harmonies, shedding some light upon the dark lyrical twists.  
As always, Donut don't do anything conventionally, the opening track, "Green Meat Stew" is a re-write of the opener from Donut comes Alive, the mandatory cover version is of The Beatles "Helter Skelter", the vocals replaced by lead trombone, "I've got blisters on my lips" comes the cry at the end. (rateyourmusic.com)
